LG-11422: Provide Sender ID for UK SMS (#9456)

changelog: Internal, Telephony, Provide Sender ID for UK SMS

Return false from `expired_for_interval?` if the last auth event was not a remember device event (#9458)

The remember device concern is used to check if the remember device interval is expired requiring a user to reauthenticate. That check is performed on these lines:

https://github.com/18F/identity-idp/blob/f8ee126760a802eaa33de4d0786c120c50f16961/app/controllers/saml_idp_controller.rb#L24C29-L24C29

https://github.com/18F/identity-idp/blob/f8ee126760a802eaa33de4d0786c120c50f16961/app/controllers/openid_connect/authorization_controller.rb#L21

It looks like the `expired_for_interval?` was recently changed to return true if remember device was used at any point and is now expired (ref: https://github.com/18F/identity-idp/pull/9335/files#diff-82060fb86bc64910b8186479a6f620e6ba44b007ca059e082c468f29702cf142R56). As a result, a user is prompted to re-authenticate if their remember device session is expired, regardless of whether they have already re-authenticated.

This commit reverts to the original behavior to address this bug.

pull_request.title: LG-10913 remove ssn redirects
pull_request.body:
## 🎫 [Ticket](https://cm-jira.usa.gov/browse/LG-10913)

## 🛠 Summary of changes

Deleted redirects for GET and PUT methods from `/in_person_proofing/ssn`. This route used to handle the old FSM navigation, but with the deprecation and removal of the IPP SSN FSM step and subsequent replacement with a controller, this route is no longer needed. The redirects were put in place to ensure a seamless rollout for users.

## 📜 Testing Plan

- [ ] Confirm that attempting a GET or PUT request to `/in_person_proofing/ssn` returns a 404 error rather than a 307.

review.body:
> [@eileen-nava](https://github.com/eileen-nava) , only a general comment, is any of this may be useful with coming selfie check related request/response?

This is a good question.  

I don’t think we’d reintroduce any of the deleted methods in the lexis nexis client, especially since we aren’t planning to have front and back images on different pages.  

I also don’t think there was a benefit to having `LexisNexisResponse`, which was never instantiated anywhere in the app, and then having the separate `TrueIDResponse` class that inherits from `LexisNexisResponse`.  I would have kept `LexisNexisResponse` if we were going to introduce another class that inherits from it, but I don’t see that in our future plans.
